<h1 class="title">Toshiba shows an ultra-thin flexible 3&quot; OLED display prototype</h1>
      

	  
  
    
	 
  <div class="node">
        
    
    
        	
    	<div class="left-side-sharing-block"><div><a href="http://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-count="vertical" data-via="oledinfo">Tweet</a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js"></script></div><div class="side-sharing-button"><iframe src="http://www.facebook.com/plugins/like.php?app_id=204258876285823&amp;href=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.oled-info.com%2Ftoshiba-shows-ultra-thin-flexible-3-oled-display-prototype&amp;send=false&amp;layout=box_count&amp;width=50&amp;show_faces=false&amp;action=like&amp;colorscheme=light&amp;font=arial&amp;height=60" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" 
	    	style="margin-left:5px;border:none; overflow:hidden; width:50px; height:60px;" allowTransparency="true"></iframe></div><div class="side-sharing-button"><g:plusone size="tall"></g:plusone></div><div class="side-sharing-button"><script src="http://www.stumbleupon.com/hostedbadge.php?s=5"></script></div></div><span class="taxonomy"><ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_59 first"><a href="/tags/flexible_oleds" rel="tag" title="">Flexible OLED</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_12"><a href="/tags/technical_research" rel="tag" title="">Technical / Research</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_72 last"><a href="/tags/companies/tmdisplay" rel="tag" title="">TMDisplay</a></li>
</ul></span>    
        <div class="content" ><p><em><strong>Update: We have some info and a new photo of Toshiba's flexible OLED prototype. See below.</strong></em></p><p>Toshiba is showing an ultra thin (0.1mm) flexible 3" 160x120 OLED display prototype that weights just one gram. The OLED is built using an oxide semiconductor TFT (IGZO) unto a plastic substrate. Toshiba says that they will be able to start producing displays based on this production method by 2014 or 2015.</p><center><br/>  <div class="block block-block" id="block-block-28">
        <div class="content"><script type="text/javascript"><!--
google_ad_client = "pub-4785989504530480";
google_ad_type = "text_image";
google_ad_channel = "0316165879+3147100765+8930241030"
google_ad_width = 336;
google_ad_height = 280;
google_ad_format = "336x280_as";
google_color_border = "003366";
google_color_bg = "FFFF66";
google_color_link = "000000";
google_color_url = "0066CC";
google_color_text = "000000";
google_ui_features = "rc:10";
//--></script>
<script type="text/javascript"
src="http://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/show_ads.js">
</script></div>
 </div>
</center><p><span class="inline inline-center"><img src="http://www.oled-info.com/files/images/toshiba-ultra-thin-flexible-OLED-prototype_0.jpg" alt="Toshiba ultra-thin flexible OLED prototype photo" title="Toshiba ultra-thin flexible OLED prototype photo"  class="image image-_original " width="230" height="160" /></span></p><p>Toshiba's OLED uses white OLED material with color filters. The architecture is bottom-emission. Toshiba says that the managed to lower the process temperature to 200Â°C, and so were able to use the plastic substrate.</p>

<p><span class="inline inline-center"><a href="/toshiba-flexible-oled-prototype-sid-2011"><img src="http://www.oled-info.com/files/images/toshiba-flexible-oled-sid-2011.img_assist_custom-300x195.jpg" alt="Toshiba flexible OLED prototype (SID 2011) " title="Toshiba flexible OLED prototype (SID 2011) "  class="image image-img_assist_custom-300x195 " width="300" height="195" /></a></span></p><p>That's interesting news as the<a href="http://www.oled-info.com/toshiba-scrap-plans-oled-production-focus-lcds"> latest news from Toshiba Mobile Displays was that they have scrapped their OLED display plans</a> (but continue to work on OLED lighting panels). So perhaps this is another company within Toshiba, and in any case it's currently just a research program.</p><p>via <a href="http://www.crunchgear.com/2011/05/18/toshiba-protoypes-ultra-thin-rollable-oled/">Crunchgear</a></p><div class="image-clear"></div></div>
    
        <div class="links">
